The new layout must strictly follow the structure an d examples shown in `Format_Example.xlsx`, leaving any unknown fields blank.  

Save the transformed data as `Processed.xlsx` in the workspace. List the records in reverse chronological order, starting from December 2024 and moving backward, and include only months with at least some data.

{"code":"import pandas as pd
from pathlib import Path

in_path = Path('/workspace/dumps/workspace/Household_Appliances.xlsx')
out_path = Path('/workspace/dumps/workspace/Processed.xlsx')

# Read only columns A:M (Time + 3 blocks of 4 columns)
# Use two header rows to capture category and metric names
try:
    df = pd.read_excel(in_path, sheet_name='Sheet1', header=[0,1], usecols='A:M')
except Exception as e:
    print('READ_FAIL', e)
    raise

# Identify Time column (first col)
# Sometimes second-level header for Time is NaN; normalize column names
cols = []
for top, sub in df.columns:
    top = str(top) if top is not None else ''
    sub = str(sub) if sub is not None else ''
    cols.append((top.strip(), sub.strip()))

# Build mapping for categories
category_map = {
    'Sales Volume of Household Refrigerators': 'Household Refrigerators',
    'Production Volume of Air Conditioners': 'Air Conditioners',
    'Production Volume of Household Washing Machines': 'Household Washing Machines',
}
metric_order = [
    'Current Period Sales(Ten Thousand Units)',
    'Accumulated Sales (Ten Thousand Units)',
    'Year-on-Year Growth (%)',
    'Accumulated Growth (%)',
]

# Extract time series
# Find which column pair corresponds to Time
time_col_idx = None
for i, (t, s) in enumerate(cols):
    if t.lower() == 'time':
        time_col_idx = i
        break

if time_col_idx is None:
    raise RuntimeError('Time column not found')

# Create a Series for time
time_series = df.iloc[:, time_col_idx]
# Coerce to datetime
time_dt = pd.to_datetime(time_series, errors='coerce')

# Build long DataFrame
records = []

# Determine column indices for each category and metric
for i, (top, sub) in enumerate(cols):
    if top in category_map and sub in metric_order:
        cat = category_map[top]
        metric = sub
        records.append({'cat': cat, 'metric': metric, 'col_idx': i})

# Pivot: for each category, collect its 4 metric columns
cats = sorted(set(r['cat'] for r in records), key=lambda x: ['Household Refrigerators','Air Conditioners','Household Washing Machines'].index(x))

rows_out = []
for row_idx in range(len(df)):
    t = time_dt.iloc[row_idx]
    if pd.isna(t):
        continue
    # Build data for each category
    for cat in cats:
        row_vals = {
            'Time': t,
            'Appliance types': cat,
            'Current Period Sales(Ten Thousand Units)': None,
            'Accumulated Sales (Ten Thousand Units)': None,
            'Year-on-Year Growth (%)': None,
            'Accumulated Growth (%)': None,
        }
        # fill values
        for rec in records:
            if rec['cat'] == cat:
                val = df.iloc[row_idx, rec['col_idx']]
                row_vals[rec['metric']] = val
        # If all data fields are NaN/None, skip this row
        data_fields = [row_vals[m] for m in metric_order]
        if all(pd.isna(v) for v in data_fields):
            continue
        rows_out.append(row_vals)

out_df = pd.DataFrame(rows_out)

# Convert percentages from fraction to percent numbers
for col in ['Year-on-Year Growth (%)', 'Accumulated Growth (%)']:
    out_df[col] = pd.to_numeric(out_df[col], errors='coerce') * 100

# Filter to include only months with at least some data and time <= 2024-12
# First, keep only rows with Time <= 2024-12 end of month
cutoff = pd.Timestamp('2024-12-31')
out_df = out_df[out_df['Time'] <= cutoff]

# Keep only months where there is at least one row with any non-null metric
# (already ensured per-row has at least some data), so grouping not necessary

# Sort in reverse chronological order
out_df = out_df.sort_values(by='Time', ascending=False)

# Format Time as YYYY-MM
out_df['Time'] = out_df['Time'].dt.strftime('%Y-%m')

# Reorder columns to match example
out_df = out_df[['Time', 'Appliance types', 'Current Period Sales(Ten Thousand Units)',
                 'Accumulated Sales (Ten Thousand Units)', 'Year-on-Year Growth (%)',
                 'Accumulated Growth (%)']]

# Write to Excel
with pd.ExcelWriter(out_path, engine='openpyxl') as writer:
    out_df.to_excel(writer, index=False, sheet_name='Processed')

print('OK', len(out_df))
","filename":"transform_household_appliances.py","timeout":120}

{"code":"import pandas as pd
from pathlib import Path

in_path = Path('/workspace/dumps/workspace/Household_Appliances.xlsx')
out_path = Path('/workspace/dumps/workspace/Processed.xlsx')

# Read full sheet with two header rows
try:
    df = pd.read_excel(in_path, sheet_name='Sheet1', header=[0,1])
except Exception as e:
    print('READ_FAIL', e)
    raise

# Normalize column tuples
cols = []
for top, sub in df.columns:
    top = '' if pd.isna(top) else str(top).strip()
    sub = '' if pd.isna(sub) else str(sub).strip()
    cols.append((top, sub))

# Build mapping for categories
category_map = {
    'Sales Volume of Household Refrigerators': 'Household Refrigerators',
    'Production Volume of Air Conditioners': 'Air Conditioners',
    'Production Volume of Household Washing Machines': 'Household Washing Machines',
}
metric_order = [
    'Current Period Sales(Ten Thousand Units)',
    'Accumulated Sales (Ten Thousand Units)',
    'Year-on-Year Growth (%)',
    'Accumulated Growth (%)',
]

# Find time column index (top level header == 'Time')
time_col_idx = None
for i, (t, s) in enumerate(cols):
    if t.lower() == 'time':
        time_col_idx = i
        break
if time_col_idx is None:
    raise RuntimeError('Time column not found')

# Time series
time_series = pd.to_datetime(df.iloc[:, time_col_idx], errors='coerce')

# Determine column indices for each category+metric within A:M region if possible, but robustly across all
records = []
for i, (top, sub) in enumerate(cols):
    if top in category_map and sub in metric_order:
        records.append({'cat': category_map[top], 'metric': sub, 'col_idx': i})

# Ensure we have expected 12 metric columns (3 cats * 4 metrics)
# Some files may have extra duplicated blocks; we keep the first occurrence per cat+metric
seen = set()
unique_records = []
for rec in records:
    key = (rec['cat'], rec['metric'])
    if key not in seen:
        seen.add(key)
        unique_records.append(rec)
records = unique_records

# Assemble output rows
rows_out = []
for row_idx in range(len(df)):
    t = time_series.iloc[row_idx]
    if pd.isna(t):
        continue
    # We only want up to Dec 2024
    if t > pd.Timestamp('2024-12-31'):
        continue
    for cat in ['Household Refrigerators','Air Conditioners','Household Washing Machines']:
        row_vals = {
            'Time': t,
            'Appliance types': cat,
            'Current Period Sales(Ten Thousand Units)': pd.NA,
            'Accumulated Sales (Ten Thousand Units)': pd.NA,
            'Year-on-Year Growth (%)': pd.NA,
            'Accumulated Growth (%)': pd.NA,
        }
        for rec in records:
            if rec['cat'] == cat:
                val = df.iloc[row_idx, rec['col_idx']]
                row_vals[rec['metric']] = val
        # Keep only if there is at least one non-null among the 4 metrics
        data_fields = [row_vals[m] for m in metric_order]
        if all(pd.isna(v) for v in data_fields):
            continue
        rows_out.append(row_vals)

out_df = pd.DataFrame(rows_out)

# Convert growth fractions to percentages
for col in ['Year-on-Year Growth (%)', 'Accumulated Growth (%)']:
    out_df[col] = pd.to_numeric(out_df[col], errors='coerce') * 100

# Sort reverse chronological
out_df = out_df.sort_values(by='Time', ascending=False)

# Format time as YYYY-MM
out_df['Time'] = pd.to_datetime(out_df['Time'], errors='coerce').dt.strftime('%Y-%m')

# Reorder columns
out_df = out_df[['Time', 'Appliance types', 'Current Period Sales(Ten Thousand Units)',
                 'Accumulated Sales (Ten Thousand Units)', 'Year-on-Year Growth (%)',
                 'Accumulated Growth (%)']]

# Write to Excel
with pd.ExcelWriter(out_path, engine='openpyxl') as writer:
    out_df.to_excel(writer, index=False, sheet_name='Processed')

print('OK', len(out_df))
","filename":"transform_household_appliances_v2.py","timeout":120}
